We first note that the only “Fixed Assets” posting in the file is the initial posting on 2023‑12‑31 which sets the fixed assets at 8,000,000.00. (All the other purchase transactions are for items with product‐codes like F002, F003, etc. In this context those are “products” held for sale rather than items recorded as fixed assets.) 

However, the file does include depreciation entries. In this period we have the following two depreciation entries:

 • On 2024‑01‑01, a “Depreciation” entry of 45,746.47  
 • On 2024‑02‑01, a “Depreciation” entry of 45,741.88

These two depreciation amounts are assumed to be accumulated depreciation on the fixed assets. In order to compute the “net” fixed assets at period‐end we subtract the total depreciation from the initial fixed assets value.

Step by step:

1. Fixed assets initial value = 8,000,000.00  
2. Total depreciation = 45,746.47 + 45,741.88 = 91,488.35  
3. Fixed assets net (end) = 8,000,000.00 – 91,488.35 = 7,908,511.65

Thus the answer is as follows:

{
  "solution": {
    "fixed assets net Initial Value": "8000000.00",
    "fixed assets net End Value": "7908511.65"
  }
}
